With the commitment to offer high-quality education in a safe and welcoming environment, the District and the Jefferson County Education Association (JCEA) and Jeffco ESPA (JESPA) have agreed to terms for working conditions for the 2020-21 school year with a Memorandum of Understanding for each group. The District worked collaboratively with teams from both associations to reach terms for a safe work environment to ensure we can open our schools to in-person learning.

Read more at:
https://jps.news/JCEAmou
https://jps.news/JESPAmou

shared_text:
Jefferson County Public Health
August 31 at 5:40 PM ¬∑

Labor Day is the last holiday of the summer and for many, the last chance to get out and celebrate with loved ones. However, in the weeks following the July Fourth holiday, we saw a surge in COVID-19 cases. Many of those COVID-19 cases were linked to private gatherings and parties, like BBQs, birthdays and weddings. It‚Äôs important to make sure that as you spend the holiday celebrating with your loved ones, you do so in a way that keeps you and your community safe. Join us each day this week as we share tips to make your Labor Day as safe as possible.
For tips on celebrating safely, visit https://www.jeffco.us/CivicAlerts.aspx?AID=1333

During the remote learning period of August 24th ‚Äì September 4th, all Jeffco students will have access to school meals!
There are a few changes to our meal service:
- Meals are no longer universally free. See meal prices below.
- Students must complete a new Free and Reduced Meal Application for the 20-21 school year.
- Students who qualify for free and reduced-price meals will receive breakfast and lunch at no cost.
- Please use School Caf√© to deposit money in student accounts before school starts.
- All students receiving meals must have their student ID number at the pickup sites.

Remote Learning Meal Prices
Elementary Breakfast: $2.25
Secondary Breakfast: $2.50
Elementary Lunch: $3.50
Secondary Lunch: $3.75

Visit www.schoolcafe.com to complete a Free and Reduced Meal Application and to deposit money to your student‚Äôs account.

We look forward to seeing you at our meal pickup locations soon!

Throughout August, graduating seniors were given a badge of honor as they ‚Äúwalked‚Äù for graduation. Each graduating senior received a resilience cord in deep purple, to cherish as a token of their milestone in graduating, and as a thread to their future paths.

post_text:
So, what will bus service look like this school year?

In accordance with the CDC and JCPH guidelines, bus capacity will be restricted to 22-24 passengers or less depending on the school bus size. Below are additional expectations for student riders who are eligible:

- All students will be required to wear face coverings.
- Parents will be expected to take their child‚Äôs temperature before leaving the house and to withhold an ill student from riding the bus.
- Bused students will be symptom screened upon arrival at school.
- Students must sit one per seat on the school bus starting from the second row of the school bus.
- If students live in the same residence, those students will be required to sit together in the same seat to increase rider capacity.
- Students will load the bus from the rear and unload from the front.
- Students will not be allowed to change seats while riding on the bus.

Have other questions? Visit our RestartJeffco.org FAQ page to get the answer to many of our commonly asked community questions.

post_text:
‚ÄúI would say it will look similar, but better. We are setting up expectations, trainings and support so that all of our teachers, system-wide, will be using a common learning management system (often referred to as LMS). This is a way to organize delivery of content and instructional materials, [as well as] lessons and tools for kids to use. This way, when there‚Äôs a consistent learning management system across a grade-level, a classroom, or a school, the familiarity of how to use that resource is the same for kids in that grade-level or school. That will help teachers to organize in a common way that is familiar with students and also will be familiar for our parents. Consistency in a common learning management system is one thing we learned from thousands and thousands of bits of feedback we collected from our teachers, our community and our students.‚Äù

Chief Academic Officer Matt Flores talked to 9NEWS (KUSA) about our Restart Jeffco plans. You can read the article via the link below.

Introducing... the Jeffco Public Schools' Virtual Calm Room! We invite all students, staff, and families to discover helpful tools and fun activities here, all aimed to manage the emotions and stress we're experiencing at this time (we will be running the panda cam 24-7). Integrating purposeful pauses throughout the day to calm both your brain and body are important and the Calm Room makes it that much easier. Whether it's a live animal cam, yoga practice, or calming visual videos - there's a resource for any mindset or need!

https://www.jeffcopublicschools.org/services/health_services/healthy_schools/virtual_calm_room

Nothing like a good time-lapse video to keep an eye on construction progress! As our contractors begin prepping for their work at Alameda International, they set up a camera so we can follow along. The school is undergoing a major makeover - with a major building addition with classrooms, a library, music/choral suite, new building entry, interior renovations, security enhancements, and updated furnishing. We will be sure to share more videos once the construction is in full swing!

If you want to know more about construction and projects happening across Jeffco, head over to Jeffcobuilds.org. #jeffcobuilds

Today we honor and recognize Juneteenth - it is both a celebratory and somber holiday to commemorate the end of slavery in the United States. This is a day to learn, engage, and reflect on our country's past, present, and future.

Do you celebrate Juneteenth already? If so, tell us about your traditions. Planning on celebrating this year with your family? Share what you have planned to honor this important day. #juneteenth2020

https://www.tolerance.org/magazine/teaching-juneteenth

post_text:
Jeffco Public Schools athletics and activities will be restored beginning June 22 under a phased-in approach and set of conditions to ensure the health and safety of participants.

More information will be released next week about these conditions, participation guidelines, timing, and other details.

We appreciate the patience and understanding of our student athletes and their families as we prepare our facilities and define the information they will need about the restart of athletic programs. Coaches and athletic directors are excited to welcome our athletes and participants back to our fields and programs.

The previously announced restrictions for non-district use of facilities (outside organizations renting our fields and facilities) remains in place through July 1.

Coaches and athletic directors are excited to welcome our athletes and participants back to our fields and programs.

The previously announced restrictions for non-district use of facilities (outside organizations renting our fields and facilities) remains in place through July 1.

post_text:
Our school nurses do so much more than fix-up playground scrapes (but they do that as well!).

School nurses are the bridge linking school health with academics. Whether coordinating health condition management with instructors or instructing staff with Stop the Bleed and CPR/First Aid, they are at the forefront of assisting students, families, and staff with school health. They provide drug prevention and intervention services to high school students, screen for hearing and vision deficits, ensure immunization compliancy, coordinate concussion management, and provide emotional support to all. They are an extremely well-educated, empathetic group of professionals. We are so lucky to have their experience and dedication in our district.

We ‚ù§Ô∏è our school nurses! #nationalschoolnurseday

post_text:
Today we remember all those who were lost 21 years ago. We hold them in our hearts, each and every day. We honor their light, their love, and their dreams. ‚ù§Ô∏è

In honor of their memories, our Colorado community commits to a Day of Service every April 20th. Even though we are being asked to stay at home and practice social distancing, we can still engage in acts of service and gratitude. You can still connect with your community, commit a random act of kindness, share a note of thanks, and stand in solidarity with our everyday heroes who are working to keep our communities safe, healthy, and well-stocked.

#wearecolumbine #jeffcostrong

Just because we are social distancing doesn't mean music lessons have to stop!

Joey is a Jeffco 6th grader that was practicing his violin outside his home as we continue social distancing. Joey's neighbor Doris, an avid player herself and part of our nation's Greatest Generation, heard him from next door and asked Joey if she could join him. She taught him to play Twinkle Twinkle Little Star, without sheet music. AMAZING!

post_text: We know, we love our playgrounds just as much as you. But to stay in compliance with Jefferson County Colorado Government's Stay-at-Home order - we ask you to please refrain from visiting and playing on any Jeffco Public Schools playground, field, or facility space. According to the Stay-at-Home order, no more than four people can congregate at once. This means, no playdates at our playgrounds or group soccer games. Our facilities are being patrolled and people will be cited. We have to do our part to keep others safe and healthy. #doingmypartCO

We know this isn't the spring break you had planned. It's not what we had imagined either. But now - more than ever - it's crucial that we all do our part and practice smart social distancing.

This is Colorado and the weather forecast looks nice. If you are outside to get fresh air, please be sure to keep 6ft apart. If one of our Jefferson County Open Space trails looks too crowded? Take another route or head to a different trail.

Looking for stay-at-home ideas? Head over to our new site - Jeffco Makes. We are posting three new activities each week, and be sure to share your projects with us!

This is tough. But we are in it together. Let's unite as a community and #doyourpartCO

Good evening, Jeffco families. We have sent our community an email this evening announcing a change to our schedule. Beginning Monday, March 16 our school buildings will be closed for in-person classes. For the entire week, through March 20, all Jeffco Public Schools facilities will be closed to non-employees. We will transition to a Remote Learning and Work Plan where students will learn from home during next week. We will send follow up communications about what this means tomorrow morning, Friday, March 13. This message will also be posted on our website. Please review it as soon as possible to ensure you are prepared. Thank you for your support.
Normal school day Friday, March 13.

post_text:
Remembering Agent Adams ~

Long time Lakewood Police Agent, and former Jeffco Public Schools Resource Officer Dave Adams, has passed away after a difficult battle with ALS.

During his SRO career, Adams would visit Jeffco classrooms to talk about drug dangers. He was also active in local Boys & Girls Clubs, and The Boy Scouts of America.

In a Facebook post, his daughter Whitney Adams wrote, "He wore many, many titles with such pride and passion. Everything he did, he did with his whole being."

Adams also wrote, "In lieu of any flowers, if you would like you make a donation to the ALS Association in Dave's honor, it would really mean a great deal to all of us." #Jeffco

We are beyond proud of Standley Lake High School teacher Sam Long, who was honored at this month's Human Rights Campaign THRIVE Conference.

Sam is a biology teacher at Standley Lake High School and the co-founder of Colorado Transgender/Nonbinary Educators Network. The community-organizing group works to support transgender and non-binary teachers and others working in the education system. Sam‚Äôs presence in the classroom as an openly transgender teacher, along with his advocacy work, sets an example for LGBTQ youth everywhere.

"When you plant lettuce, if it does not grow well, you don't blame the lettuce. You look into the reasons it is not doing well. It may need fertilizer, or more water, or less sun. You never blame the lettuce"

Our Title I families really turned out to learn more about Social Emotional Learning in Jeffco last night! Families and caregivers learned what social-emotional education looks like in the classroom, plus ways they can help at home. Special thanks to Dr. Erin Sullivan, Coordinator of Social Emotional Learning Specialists, for her presentation.

Children that attended were able to make crafts, create electric circuits, and explore their own creativity. It was a great night for learning together!

Join Jefferson Center for Mental Health and Jeffco Public Schools to share your perspectives and talk about children‚Äôs mental health and substance use, including what‚Äôs working, what resources are needed in the community, and how we can all work together to create a brighter future where mental health matters and is accessible to all.

LOCATION: St Anthony Hospital
11600 W 2nd Place

post_text:
Wish Week Comes To D'Evelyn~

Students and staff at D'Evelyn Jr. Sr. High joined forces with Make-A-Wish Colorado to organize a Friday afternoon pep rally in honor of nine-year-old Jalen, a Colorado Springs boy fighting cancer.

Jalen's wish was to be an astronaut. He was greeted with a thunderous roar as he ran out into the packed D'Evelyn gym in his astronaut suit and helmet. The event featured student performances, orange bucket fundraising, a visit from Spiderman, games, and a special video message for Jalen from D'Evelyn grad and NASA astronaut Matthew Dominick.

As part of Wish Week, the D'Evelyn community raised over $20,000. "We are so incredibly grateful for the impact you've made," Make-A-Wish Colorado Development Manager Sarah Grosh told the crowd. "The love and the magic that you created for [Jalen] is everything that Make-A-Wish and a wish represent." Look for a JPS-TV story on the event soon. #Jeffco

post_text: We ‚ù§Ô∏è partnerships between our schools and fellow public organizations - like this one between Wilmore Davis Elementary School and City of Wheat Ridge Government to make the Anderson Park Nature Play area one designed for (and by) students!
shared_text:
City of Wheat Ridge Government
January 13 at 1:11 AM ¬∑

Anderson Park Nature Play Area Underway

Last August, Wheat Ridge Parks staff began collaborating with Wilmore-Davis Elementary students to design three pods for the nature play area to be incorporated on the east side of Anderson Park. Students completed kickoff meetings and site visits, and worked on their designs throughout the fall semester. After the site visits, the primary pathway (pictured) to the nature play area was installed.

Students will present their designs to Parks and Recreation staff and the National Wildlife Federation later this month. Construction of the nature play area at Anderson Park will begin in April.

post_text:
Because it's two days until break. And finals week. And the holiday season.

Pretty sure we all need this cat right now.

If you are feeling the stress of tests, the holidays, or anything else, we've got a few tips to help you manage the feelings and get through it all (remember, there are cookies on the other side of Friday):
* Take short breaks from studying/work - get outside for a few minutes and enjoy some fresh air and sunshine.
* Stay hydrated! And be sure to eat a good meal pre-test/work (pack snacks as well).
* In a moment of stress, focus on your breath. Slowly in through your nose, hold, then even slower out through your mouth.
* Get up from your desk to do a few short stretches or 'brain gym' exercises.
* Tell yourself "I got this!".

Good luck and remember, hang in there!

We have some incredible people working in Jeffco. And at last night's board meeting, we honored two groups whose work makes this district what it is!

First, the board honored The Colorado Council for Learning Disabilities Para educators of the year. The honorees are Geraldine Hooper with Glennon Heights Elementary School, Linda Becerra with Ken Caryl Middle School, and Becky Faurer with Adams Elementary School.

The second recognition was to Jeffco's research and assessment team. They were recognized by the American Educational Research Association (AERA) local affiliate in the Rocky Mountain region for their research paper entitled ‚ÄúThe Concerns-Based Adoption Model and Strategic Plan Evaluation: Multiple Methodologies to Understand Complex Change.‚Äù The honorees are Kate Olson, Ph.D., Katie Lannan, Ph.D., John Cumming, Ph.D., Heather MacGillivary, Ph.D., and Kevin Richards.

Congrats to all! Thank you for your dedication to our students, families, and community!

Welcome to Jeffco ~

Two new Jeffco Board of Education members took the oath of office at a special meeting at the Ed Center in Golden Monday night.

The Honorable Philip J. McNulty, District Court Chief Judge of the 1st Judicial District, administered the oath to newly elected Board of Education members Stephanie Schooley (District 3), who replaces outgoing BOE member Ali Lasell, and Susan Miller (District 4), who replaces outgoing BOE member Amanda Stevens.

At the same meeting, Jeffco BOE President Ron Mitchell announced he was relinquishing the presidency due to health reasons. Mitchell, who will remain a board member, was succeeded by BOE member Susan Harmon following a board vote. #Jeffco

All Jeffco Public Schools buildings and facilities will be closed Tuesday, November 26, 2019, due to inclement weather. Employees do not need to report to work (unless otherwise notified by your supervisor), and all facilities are closed. Access to any building for any reason needs to be approved by security dispatch prior to entering a building. All School Age Enrichment (SAE) programs, after school activities, child care services, and meetings in Jeffco Public Schools facilities are canceled. No Jeffco Public Schools transportation services will be provided for services within or outside the district.

Stay safe out there, Jeffco!

post_text:
Months before walls come down, equipment moves in, and new school additions take shape, a group of dedicated and passionate school community members works to reimagine their building and educational spaces.

These Design Advisory Groups (DAGs) -- like this all-star group at Lumberg Elementary School -- start at the beginning. How do we want students to experience our programs? What does our staff need to be fully able to execute their jobs? And how do we make our school an inviting and safe space for all?

These fun, but tough, questions are guided by our fantastic local architects, including @moaarch, who design spaces that meet the unique needs of each school -- taking all of the big, crazy ideas and turning them into a reality. We are excited to follow along at Lumberg Elementary School and many others as the design process continues. You can learn more about all of our projects at jeffcobuilds.org.

#Jeffcobuilds
